Anyone who smokes has a higher risk of losing teeth.
Those who smoke do not only harm the lungs, but also the teeth - this suggests a long-term study from Potsdam.
The good news is that if you give up, the risk decreases quickly.
Smokers have a significantly increased risk of losing their teeth early.
This is according to the long-term study of an international research team, including several employees of the German Institute for Nutrition Research (DIfE) in Potsdam.
In comparison to non-smokers, the risk of losing their teeth prematurely was 2.5 to 3.6 times higher.
The scientists had observed more than 23,300 participants.
The main causes of tooth loss are caries and inflammation of the gums, the DIfE emphasizes.
For this periodontitis, smoking is a risk factor, the authors emphasize.
The link between smoking and tooth loss therefore stems from more frequent gum infections in smokers.
It is not clear to what extent smoking also increases the risk of caries.
However, people who quit smoking could reduce their risk within a short time, the researchers write in the "Journal of Dental Research".
However, it could take more than ten years for the risk to drop back to the level of non-smokers, said lead author Thomas Dietrich of the English University of Birmingham.
One must convince people to become non-smokers, said study leader Heiner Boeing of the DIfE: "Smoking shortens the life span."
Not smoking is good for the lungs and vessels and, according to our findings, leads to good dental health until old age.
In Germany, more than 20 percent of the population aged 65 to 74 are affected by toothlessness, the DIfE said.
Previous research suggests that smoking increases the risk of early tooth loss.
The new long-term study underpins the findings.
