EU Commission proposes new court in dispute over TTIP
In order to defuse the dispute over the planned transatlantic free trade agreement TTIP, the EU Commission has proposed a comprehensive reform of the current arbitration system.
The controversial private arbitration bodies for disputes between corporations and states should therefore be replaced by a more transparent system, which corresponds significantly to more traditional courts.
"We want to set up a system that citizens trust," EU Commissioner Cecilia Malmström said at the presentation.
The Swede intends to introduce the proposal as a European negotiating position in the free trade talks with the United States.
The German government has announced support.
TTIP is the largest free trade zone in the world with 800 million people.
The plans for reforming the current arbitration process specifically stipulate that the EU and the US jointly select independent judges for a new Investment Court.
They should come equally from the EU, the US and third countries.
For the first time, there is also a second instance.
It would allow appeals to be made against judgments.
So far, the parties to the proceedings have agreed on arbitrators, and there was no possibility of appeal against their judgments.
In the discussion of recent months, it became clear that citizens did not trust the old ISDS system in terms of fairness and justice, Malmström commented.
In the long term, she wants to work towards an international investment court.
There, for example, disputes between Chinese companies and EU countries could also be resolved.
The investor-state arbitration proceedings (ISDS) demanded mainly by large corporations are regarded as one of the main reasons for the great resistance in Europe to TTIP.
Traditional arbitral tribunals are criticized by opponents as a kind of parallel justice through which companies can claim damages at the expense of taxpayers, lift national laws or enforce a reduction in consumer and environmental standards.
In initial statements, anti-TTIP organizations such as Campact described the EU Commission’s proposals as inadequate.
It was criticized above all that they should not apply to the already negotiated free trade agreement with Canada (Ceta).
The German economic secretary Matthias Machnig (SPD) described the plans as great progress.
The Commission takes into account in the reform essential points that Federal Minister of Economic Affairs Sigmar Gabriel worked out with other EU trade ministers in the spring.
The old system of private arbitration is off the table.
The French government also welcomed Malmström’s plans.
The European business association BusinessEurope warned against restricting the legal opportunities of the economy with too many new rules.
Especially small and medium-sized enterprises could be disadvantaged, it said.
When the talks on the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP) could be concluded, remained unclear on Wednesday.
