In all these measurements, about a quarter of democratic voters have no opinion of Sanders.
As questions continue to be asked about Hillary Clinton’s use of a personal email address and server during her tenure as Secretary of State, most Democratic voters of the primaries are satisfied with her explanation of the matter and say it has not influenced her opinions overall.
But it’s a different story in the American public as a whole.
Half of Americans are now dissatisfied with their statement, while only about a third are satisfied.
Public opinion on this was divided in March, shortly after the problem came to light.
Most Americans said the email controversy had no impact on their general opinions of Clinton, although 36 percent said their opinions of her had worsened.
It’s mostly Republicans, more than six out of 10, who say their views of Clinton have gotten worse.
Although Clinton is considered honest and trustworthy by her party voters, this remains a problem for her among registered voters as a whole: only 32 percent see her as honest and trustworthy, 8% less than last month, and 15 points less since May.
62% of voters don’t think they’re an honest and trustworthy person.
