At their most anticipated meeting in the year, Federal Reserve strategists spend two days this week sitting around a 27-foot Honduras-Mahagoni table to decide if it’s time to raise the Leitzins for the first time in nearly a decade.
Threatening over them, at one end of the ornate, two-storey meeting room, is a mural of the United States.
The card is a reminder that Fed Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the nation’s economic interests ahead of all other things.
The central bank has a double mandate from Congress: to maximize U.S. employment and keep prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, Fed leaders have recognized that there is an unwritten third mandate: financial stability.
And this third mandate could be the X-factor in a decision that is too narrow to predict it. It will be announced on Thursday whether the U.S. economy is ready to be weaned from the unprecedented incentive of the near-zero short-term interest rate since the end of 2008.
Although most of the economy’s data shows it is growing solidly, recent turbulence in global financial markets could scare already cautious Fed representatives to step up this volatility by raising the interest rate on federal bonds – even if it’s only a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the most important thing they are watching,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the increased uncertainty around the global market is enough justification to continue waiting,” she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed is going to do, which in itself is insecure the financial market.
