If she does, “she should go very far in her statement to calm the financial markets so that they don’t panic.”
Other experts argued that a rate hike would calm financial markets because it would eliminate uncertainty about when the Fed will trade.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed well on track to raise the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would test the strength of the recovery in the US.
Yellen had said in the spring and early summer that despite the complaints from liberals that more economic progress would be needed, she expected an increase in the rate this year.
Although job creation slowed in August, the improvement in the labour market was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level that the Fed sees as full employment.
Wage increases have shown signs of recovery.
And although inflation was constantly below the annual target of 2% of the central bank, the Fed representatives said the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
“The economy can cope with higher interest rates and needs them because of the tension in the labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world shrank at the end of last month, after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial average fell more than 16% below its peak in May, when investors feared a slowdown in the Chinese economy would throttle global growth.
The market has recovered slightly this month, with the Dow now almost 10% below the high of May.
For Fed representatives, market turbulence affects the complex calculation of when to raise interest rates.
“If the events in the financial markets and the news about the weakness of the Chinese economy had not occurred in the last few weeks, they would be putting on the reins in this session,” said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior research fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Federal Reserve employee.
Now he predicts she will wait at least a month to better manage the impact.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy, and there is almost no reliable data describing developments in China," Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the Fed’s main concerns, so it should not be technically involved in its decision-making.
But in the end, the Fed has become the world’s monetary authority.
The influence of the central bank has been enormous in recent years.
The mere hint from then-leader Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “strict” its monetary expansion sparked confusion around the globe.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed representatives can be expected to not only monitor developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
Their decision-making is "more art than science," said Zachary Karabell, head of global asset management strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, VA, noted this month that “the Fed has a history of overreactions to financial market movements that are apparently not linked to economic fundamentals.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, who advocates an interest rate increase, cited decisions in 1998/1999 as an example.
A financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to cut its key interest rate by 0.75 percentage points in three sessions “despite limited noticeable impact on growth in the US,” Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed representatives reversed these cuts.
The Fed should only prioritize aspects of financial stability during a severe crisis such as the 2008 market collapse, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England interest rate setting committee.
