Stevan Hogg took the girl’s phone when this one slept, logged into an online messaging service, from which he received a series of nasty pictures of children sent to him by another user.
The girl later woke up and discovered that the phone was missing and found it in the hand of the sleeping hogg.
She looked through it, found the confusing messages and immediately alerted her mother.
The police took care of it and saw the five images, then analyzed computers found at the address and discovered "concerning" web research using terms to search for indecent images of children.
Hogg then claimed to the officials that he did it because it would lead to “pedophiles on the Internet” and then he “pretended to be a police officer to scare them off.”
Prosecutor Eilidh Robertson told the Dundee Sheriff Court, "He said it was an addiction -- that he was addicted to scaring people.
He admitted that the searches on the computer were done by him, but said it had happened because he wanted to claim to be a police officer to scare pedophiles.
He was asked about his conversations with the unknown person who sent him the pictures and asked him to send more photos.
He said he did it to lure her.
He said he was sick in his head when he was drinking, and said he wanted to see pictures of rape and murder.
Ms. Robertson added: “When the girl found the news on the phone, she called her mother and was trembling and crying.
She then saw the indecent pictures on the phone and confronted the defendant with it.
The girl was interviewed and said the defendant used computer and playstation to talk to girls who looked much younger than him.
Hogg, 23, Ward Road, Dundee, pleaded guilty in the sense of the indictment of taking indecent pictures of children on June 14, last year, breaching the terms on January 25 of this year, and not appearing in court for a hearing on March 24 of this year.
Defense attorney Gregor Sim asked that Hogg not appear in the register of sexual offenders, as it could be argued that "no significant sexual element" could be found in his offense.
