JVA Berlin-Tegel: Five-square-foot cell is inhumane
The Federal Constitutional Court has justified an ex-detainee of the Tegel prison, who was housed in a cell too small for months.
Because of the violation of their human dignity, prisoners are generally entitled to financial compensation if they are housed in too small cells.
This was decided by the Federal Constitutional Court in a decision published on Wednesday.
According to the judges, those affected can hope for money even if they were confined in the confined rooms for only a few days (Az.: 1 BvR 1127/14).
An ex-detainee was thus successful with his constitutional complaint in Karlsruhe: he was housed in the Berlin-Tegel prison between June and November 2009 in a single cell with about five square meters of floor space; the toilet was not separated spatially.
Afterwards, the man, who according to his lawyer is now again on free foot, had been transferred to a larger cell.
His official liability lawsuit for the unworthy conditions of detention against the state of Berlin failed.
But the constitutional judges revoked the ruling of the Berlin Chamber Court and dismissed the case there for re-examination.
You see the human dignity of the man hurt.
The Court of Appeal now decides on the amount of compensation.
Even if for legal reasons of the period in question only a few days of detention are decisive for the compensation, there is a claim for compensation, it said.
Otherwise, "a loss of legal protection of the personality would be to be feared."
The Court of Appeal must now clarify the amount of the compensation.
The constitutional judges have often strengthened the rights of prisoners in the past.
So they only awarded damages to a prisoner in April because he was imprisoned naked in a cell.
According to a 2011 decision, the multiple occupancy of a cell without a separate toilet is also inhumane.
Karlsruhe also confirmed on Wednesday the Berlin Constitutional Court, which had certified a prisoner in a parallel case in November 2009 an inhumane accommodation.
For three months, the plaintiff was housed in a cell of the same type as in the Karlsruhe case, between 15 and 21 hours a day.
The Berlin prisons had also come into the headlines in recent weeks because of the lack of personnel.
Prisoners are therefore kept in custody for 23 hours, the aggressiveness increases, even fights are said to have already come because of the tense situation.
According to the judicial press office, 21 jobs in Tegel are not filled due to a shortage of young people, 19 should be eliminated in 2016.
