Robotic cars: Government wants a pioneering role for Germany
According to the German government, Germany should be a technological pioneer in the change of the car.
On Wednesday, the Federal Cabinet adopted a strategy paper from the House of Transport Minister Alexander Dobrindt (CSU), which includes investments in the expansion of digital infrastructure.
Dobrindt spoke on Wednesday in Frankfurt on the edge of the car fair IAA of a "new mobility era".
Automated and networked driving will increase road safety and reduce traffic congestion, Dobrindt said.
He also wants to discuss the issue with his colleagues from the G7 countries, who also meet with representatives of industry at the IAA.
Among other things, the strategy paper of the Ministry of Transport emphasizes the importance of mobile broadband expansion and a swift transition to digital radio.
To test new technology, a test track is currently being developed on the motorway 9 in Bavaria.
So that the driver "no additional liability risks are burdened up", the Federal Government wants to "review the legal framework conditions and, where necessary, adapt them to the new developments".
For example, Germany wants to work internationally to raise the maximum speed allowed for self-driving cars from 10 to 130 kilometers per hour.
The German government also wants to work for an amendment to the Vienna Convention, which so far only provides for people as drivers.
In the case of automated driving, the car is increasingly taking the lead, the driver is becoming more and more a passenger.
The technology is primarily based on sensors and cameras that capture the environment and process the data in seconds.
According to a study submitted by the Ministry of Economic Affairs, highly automated driving on motorways will be technically possible by 2020.
Nevertheless, driverless vehicles on public roads “are to be expected far beyond 2020.”
The authors of the study estimate that the value added in the field of driver assistance systems and highly automated driving functions at the location in Germany will be around 8.4 billion euros for 2025.
"The digital networking of the car can lead to greater safety and efficiency in road traffic," said SPD transport policymaker Sören Bartol.
However, the issue of liability in the event of accidents and the security of the personal data of the drivers must be clearly clarified.
However, the Germans still see self-driving cars as sceptical – much more than French or Americans.
A survey by the Forsa Institute on behalf of the testing organisation Dekra, presented on Wednesday at the AA, concludes that only eight percent of Germans believe that autonomous cars will prevail in the next ten years, 32 percent only expect it in 20 years, 31 percent do not believe it at all.
In France, 21 percent of respondents expect autonomous cars by 2025, while 33 percent expect autonomous cars in the United States.
In any case, drivers in Germany are not yet ready to rely entirely on a self-driving vehicle.
According to a survey by the digital association Bitkom, only seven percent would agree to hand over control on all roads during the entire journey.
On the highway, this could be imagined in flowing traffic at least 15 percent, in traffic jams 45 percent.
Nearly one in four would not be allowed to control the car under any circumstances.
