Xi urges to open the economy more broadly to the world
The economy needs to open up wider outwards to foster growth, President Xi Jinping said on Tuesday to a group tasked with steering the reform.
“China should be committed to attracting foreign investment and know-how and improving strategies for business start-ups,” he said in a speech at the 16th meeting of the Central Leadership Group to deepen a comprehensive reform.
Promoting new start-ups and advancing reforms will bring new momentum and vitality and provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The leadership group has adopted a number of guidelines, including a negative list for regulating market access, relaxation of border control policies, promotion of state enterprises (SOE), taking up private capital, and overhaul of the resident reporting system.
After the statement, a negative list is created identifying the sectors and companies that are not eligible for investment.
The system is gradually tested and improved by test programs.
The initiative is significant as it assigns the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensuring a rule of law business environment and making the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also ease control over the powers conferred on the companies and ensure that companies decide how to run their business.
The statement also said that China will allow border areas to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
As part of an offer to open state-controlled sectors, further areas will be opened for private investment.
“The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of third-party-funded companies and provide better services to them,” the statement said.
In addition, it will be made easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or the "Green Card" by optimizing the requirements and facilitating the application process.
