EU wants to double mercury limit value in predatory fish
The European Commission wants to double the limit values for mercury in large predatory fish and thus expect consumers to have a significantly higher dose of the nerve agent.
The consumer organisation Foodwatch, which has a corresponding EU working paper, strongly criticized the plans: "Risks and side effects of failed industrial and environmental policies are passed on to pregnant women and young children with full force," explained Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limits of the nerve agent for large fish at the end of the food chain, such as shark or swordfish, are to be raised from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish for "economic reasons".
However, large predatory fish are already so heavily loaded with mercury that about 50 percent of the catches cannot be sold on the basis of the still applicable limits.
After doubling the limits, only 14.5 percent would be unavailable.
In return for this easing, the EU wants to tighten the limits for other fish from currently 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram.
Foodwatch called this a "trick" because smaller Friedfish, such as carp, are usually so low-loaded that they already meet the planned highs today.
The reduction in small fish is therefore "a perfidious distraction maneuver that alone helps the economy," Wolfschmidt explained.
Mercury is a heavy metal highly toxic to humans, which accumulates heavily in the food chain, especially in predatory fish.
The Federal Government warns that "already small amounts can cause damage to the nervous system, especially in the case of unborn children."
However, the Federal Environment Ministry explains on its homepage with regard to the current maximum levels that a "health hazard to the general population" is not to be expected.
Mercury gets into the environment mainly through coal combustion.
According to a written information from the Federal Ministry of the Environment, German coal-fired power plants emit more than six tons of mercury per year to the Greens’ parliamentarian Annalena Baerbock, two-thirds of the total quantity emitted in Germany.
The concentration of mercury in fish, for example in the Elbe, Rhine and Danube, was "permanently and comprehensively exceeded," the "mirror" had quoted from the paper in March.
Last year, Europe-wide warnings of mercury in fish were already among the most frequently reported health risks in the EU’s RASFF warning system.
Foodwatch calls on consumers to protest against EU plans at: www.quecksilver-action.foodwatch.de
